{{ill|Sumida River crossings|ja|隅田川の渡し|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumida River crossings|qq=}} [[File:Sunset across the Ryogoku bridge from the bank of the Sumida river at Onmagayashi.jpg|thumb|320px|{{ill|The Ferry at Fujimi|ja|葛飾北斎|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The Ferry at Fujimi|qq=}} ("{{ill|Thirty-six Views of Mount Fuji|ja|冨嶽三十六景|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Thirty-six Views of Mount Fuji|qq=}}")]] [[File:Tsukudajima no watashi old.jpg|thumb|320px|The Ferry at Tsukudajima (early Shōwa period)]]
'''Sumida River Crossings''' (隅田川の渡し, ''Sumida-gawa no Watashi'') were a collection of ferry routes and stations that once operated along the {{ill|Sumida River|ja|隅田川|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumida River|qq=}}.
For centuries, ferries served as essential transport links on the routes leading to {{ill|Mutsu Province|1=Mutsu Province|2=ja|3=陸奥国|ja|Mutsu Province|1=Mutsu Province|2=ja|3=陸奥国|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mutsu Province|qq=}} and {{ill|総州|lt=Sōshū|ja|総州|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/総州|qq=}}, particularly before the advent of widespread bridge construction. As Edo grew under the Tokugawa shogunate, the need for crossings increased. However, defensive considerations and maintenance costs limited the number of bridges, necessitating numerous ferries to connect the north and south of Edo's expanding urban area.
Throughout the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, the number of crossings steadily increased. By the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji period|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}}, there were over 20 documented ferry routes. However, following the {{ill|1923 Great Kantō earthquake|ja|関東大震災|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1923 Great Kantō earthquake|qq=}}, new bridges capable of accommodating {{ill|automobiles|ja|自動車|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/automobiles|qq=}} and {{ill|Tokyo Toden|ja|東京都電|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyo Toden|qq=}} trams gradually replaced the ferries. The last official public ferry route, "Shiomi no Watashi," ceased operations in 1966 (Shōwa 41).
Today, the only remaining operational ferry is a private route operated by {{ill|Nippon Kayaku|ja|日本化薬|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nippon Kayaku|qq=}} for its employees, connecting its Tokyo factory in {{ill|Kita-ku, Tokyo|ja|北区 (東京都)|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kita-ku, Tokyo|qq=}} to the o11osite bank in {{ill|Adachi-ku|ja|足立区|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Adachi-ku|qq=}}. This ferry is not open to the public.<ref>[http://www.mizu.gr.jp/bunkajuku/houkoku/010_20121206_arakawa.html 実施報告 船でゆく荒川-人工水路と暮らしの接点-] - {{ill|Mizkan Water Culture Center|ja|ミツカン 水の文化センター|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mizkan Water Culture Center|qq=}}, retrieved February 23, 2017.</ref>
== Major Crossings == Below is a list of notable Sumida River ferry crossings from upstream to downstream. The locations and names of these ferries changed over time, so the representative names and positions are noted.
=== Miyabori no Watashi === Also called "Kamiyabori no Watashi," this ferry operated near the current {{ill|Shinkamiya Bridge|ja|新神谷橋|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinkamiya Bridge|qq=}}. It primarily served pilgrims visiting {{ill|Sōjiji Temple|ja|總持寺 (足立区)|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōjiji Temple|qq=}} and flower-viewing visitors to the banks of the {{ill|lt=Arakawa River|Arakawa River (Kantō)|ja|荒川 (関東)|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/lt=Arakawa River|qq=}} during the Edo period. Following the construction of the {{ill|Arakawa River (Kantō)|lt=Arakawa Spillway|ja|荒川放水路|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Arakawa River (Kantō)|qq=}} in 1924 (Taishō 13), the area became isolated as a mid-river island. The crossing was eventually replaced by Shinkamiya Bridge, completed in 1965 (Shōwa 40). A signboard commemorating the ferry is installed in {{ill|Miyabori Children's Park|ja|宮堀児童遊園|en|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyabori Children's Park|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Arakawa Spillway Construction|url=http://www.ktr.mlit.go.jp/arage/|publisher=Ministry of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism|language=ja|en}}</ref>
...
